    사농경을 돌아보며 이르시길
    내가 이제 들 밖에 가서 살펴보리라
    유사를 명하여 법가를 갖추시고
    동교에 행차하사 사가를 불러
    농부를 인견하시어 위로하여 이르시길
    아, 너희 백성들이 주림을 늘 근심터니
    어지신 하느님이
    나를 아니 저버리사
    가물다가, 비가 내려
    옥토가 훔씬 젖었으니
    밭갈고 심기를
    제때를 잃지 말고
    김매고 거름주기를
    애써 부지런히 하여
    그로써 □□하여
    넉넉히 살도록 하라
    이에 부로들이 모두 천세를 부르고
    서로 격양가를 부르기를
    우리들 저 논ㆍ밭에
    벼와 오곡 심어서
    아비가 갈고 아들이 거두어
    그 덕분에 밥을 먹네
    비 안와 가물 적엔
    불이 타는 것 같더니
    비가 오고나니
    젖 먹여 기른 듯
    두드러지게 빼어나고
    쭉쭉 자라네
    우리 임금 하늘과 합하시니
    어이 풍년 아니들리
    또 답가를 부르기를
    씨 하나를 심었더니 열매가 만 개나 드리웠고
    벼 한 알을 쪼갰더니 쌀이 두 알 나오누나
    마당에 곳간에
    가려두고 쌓아놓으니
    먹고도 남을 양식
    밭의 것을 뉘 가져가리
    나라에 곡식이 남아
    백성에게 저장해 두고, 〈따로 창고를〉 봉하지 아니하네
    경사로운 이 풍년
    누가 과연 상농인고
    왕인가, 하늘인간
    아, 그 덕 높을씨고
    노래가 끝나기 전에
    훈훈한 바람이 남쪽에서 오고
    검은 구름이 서편에 일어나네
    조금 있다가 비가 다시 내려
    신이 감응하는 것 같구나
    이윽고 찌는 듯한 더위가 씻은 듯이 가시고
    길이 깨끗해지므로
    드디어 복부들에게 명하여
    거가가 환궁하실새
    연로에 북을 치고
    악사들이 줄을 지어 풍류를 아뢰네
    노랫소리 번갈아 화답하고
    듣고 보는 이 저자와 같아
    서로 동해물과 남산을 가져다가
    덕을 기리며 축수하는
    소리가 온누리를 흔든다
    아, 하늘보다 높고 땅보다 넓은 성상의 덕이여
    비를 내리시고 바람을 주심 같은 그지없는 임의 은혜여
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1370_020_0130&viewSync=OT
  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 구농(九農) : '
    value: 《주례(周禮)》에 기장ㆍ벼ㆍ콩 등의 아홉 가지 곡식[九穀]을 말하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 자묵(子墨) 객경(客卿) : '
    value: 자묵 객경(子墨客卿)은 먹[墨]을 의인(擬人)화한 것인데, 양웅(揚雄)의 우렵부(羽獵賦)에서 나왔다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 형혹(熒惑)을 몰고 희화(羲和) : '
    value: 형혹성(熒惑星)은 불을 맡은 별이고, 《서경》에 희화(羲和)는 해[日]의 나고 드는 것을 관장하는 관직이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 우연(虞淵) : '
    value: 해가 떨어지는 못이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 정백(鄭白) : '
    value: 전국 시대(戰國時代)에 수리(水利)의 기술자인 정백(鄭白)이 진(秦)나라 위수(渭水)를 이용하여 큰 수리를 일으켰다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 표기(豹起) : '
    value: 위(魏)나라 서문표(西門豹)와 오기(吳起)가 모두 서하수(西河守)가 되어 가서 장수(漳水)를 이용하여 수리를 일으켰다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 운한(雲漢)을 원망하고 : '
    value: 《시경》의 운한편(雲漢篇)은 날이 가무는 것을 걱정하여 읊은 시다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 저자를 옮기고 : '
    value: 옛날에는 날이 가물면 시장(市場)을 이전(移轉)하여 비를 비는 풍습이 있었다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 육정(六丁) : '
    value: 여섯 신장(神將)의 칭호다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 비렴(飛廉)에게 …… 모이게 하고 : '
    value: 비렴은 바람을 맡은 신(神)이요, 풍융은 비를 맡은 신이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 풍이(馮夷)에게 …… 불러서 : '
    value: 풍이(馮夷)와 해약(海若)은 모두 물귀신이다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 천일(天一) : '
    value: 《음양서(陰陽書)》에, “천일(天一)이 수(水)를 생(生)한다.”는 말이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 이삭이 합해져서 …… 드러내리니 : '
    value: 옛날에 곡식 두 줄기의 이삭이 합해져서 큰 이삭이 된 상서로운 일이 있었다.
  - key: '[주-D014] 일원(一元) : '
    value: 천지 만물을 생성(生成)시키는 한 원기란 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 구경(九經) : '
    value: 《중용》에, “정치를 하는 데는 아홉 가지의 떳떳한 법[九經]이 있으니, ‘몸을 닦는 것, 어진 이를 높이는 것, 모든 백성을 자식처럼 볼 것 등이다.’ 하였다.”
  - key: '[주-D016] 기형(璣衡)에 …… 다스리네 : '
    value: '《서경》에, “순(舜)이 선기옥형(璇璣玉衡)이란 천문(天文)의 기계를 만들어서 일월 오성(日月五星 : 七面)을 다스렸다.” 하였다.'
  - key: '[주-D017] 그로써 천공(天工)을 …… 닦으시와 : '
    value: 《서경》에, “모든 관직을 비우지 말라. 〈관직이란 것은〉 하늘의 할 일[天工]을 사람이 대신함이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 이에 신농(神農)을 …… 숭상하사 : '
    value: 신농씨(神農氏)는 농경(農耕)을 처음 발명하였고, 후직(后稷)은 곡식의 재배 방법을 발달시킨 사람이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 적전(籍田) : '
    value: 임금이 모범으로 친히 농사를 짓는 논이다.
  - key: '[주-D020] 염경(斂耕)을 살피시며 : '
    value: 《맹자》에, “임금이 들을 순시하여 봄에 가는 것[耕]을 살펴서 부족한 것을 보충해 주고, 가을에는 추수하는 것을 살펴서 넉넉하지 못한 것을 도와 준다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D021] 과연 하늘의 …… 백성으로부터요 : '
    value: 《서경》에, “하늘이 보고 듣는 것이 달리 있는 것이 아니라 하늘의 보는 것은 우리 백성이 보는 것으로부터요, 하늘이 듣는 것은 우리 백성이 듣는 것으로부터라.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D022] 참으로 …… 하지 않는도다 : '
    value: 덕을 닦고 백성을 사랑하는 정사를 하는 것은 실(實)로 하늘을 받드는 것이 되고, 겉치레로 기우제(祈雨祭)나 지내는 척하고 자기의 허물을 반성하는 척 모든 사람에게 바른 말을 하여 올리라는 교서(敎書)나 내리는 것 등은 문(文)뿐으로 실지가 없다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D023] 하늘이 탕 임금을 …… 자책(自責)하였고 : '
    value: 탕(湯)은 7년의 대한(大旱)을 만나서 상림(桑林)의 들에 나가서 친히 비를 빌면서 여섯 가지 일로써 자책(自責)하기를, “궁실(宮室)이 너무 굉장한가, 여자의 청탁(請託)이 행하는가, 뇌물이 행하는가 등 여섯 가지 허물이 있는가.” 반성한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D024] 혹 조정에 있는 …… 없지 못하였고 : '
    value: 요(堯)의 시대에는 공공(共工)ㆍ환도(讙兜)ㆍ곤(鯀)ㆍ삼묘(三苗) 등의 네 흉한 사람이 있었다. 순(舜)의 때에 이르러 비로소 제거하였다.
  - key: '[주-D025] 혹 군신(君臣)의 …… 없지 않았고 : '
    value: 탕(湯)은 걸(桀)의 신하이면서 백성이 도탄(塗炭)에 빠진 것을 차마 볼 수 없어서 걸을 내쫓고 자기가 나라를 빼앗고는, “나는 부끄러운 덕이 있다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D026] 우리 성상께서 …… 피(避)하시고 : '
    value: 옛날에는 큰 천재(天災)가 있으면, 임금이 반성하고 자책하는 뜻으로 정전(正殿)을 피하였다.
  - key: '[주-D027] 음즐(陰騭) : '
    value: 《서경》에서 나온 말인데, 하늘이 가만히 돕는다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D028] 나라에 곡식이 남아 …… 봉하지 아니하네 : '
    value: 인정(仁政)을 하는 임금은 재물을 국고(國庫)에 저장하여 두는 것보다 백성이 잘 사는 그것이 곧 나라의 재물을 백성에게 저장하여 둠이 된다는 것이다.
english:
  title: A Rhapsody on Welcome Rain
  author: Yu Yang-chun
  language: eng
  text: "In the twenty-third year of Chenghua, in the fifth month of summer, on the sixteenth day, the people languished for rain. The earth cracked beneath the relentless sun. Seven days passed. Then on xinyu came the first drops. On dingmao, torrents descended—the nine roads ran with water, the four marshes brimmed to overflowing.\n\nThe people danced in the fields. The ministers rejoiced in the court. All cried out: \"Harvest is assured! Abundance swells forth!\" They said, \"This is the rain's work—but whose power brings it?\" Everyone hailed the prosperity, declaring: \"It is our King's virtue!\" They raised their hands and made obeisance, bringing word to the throne.\n\nThe King said: \"No. Give thanks to Heaven.\"\n\nHe proceeded to the Hall of Southern Winds and summoned the Minister of Agriculture to discuss the governance of the nine grains and to celebrate the flourishing of ten thousand crops. Then he commanded the poet Zimozike: \"You who fathom the nature of all things, who penetrate the generation of yin and yang—exalt the work of rain, celebrate Heaven's virtue. Make your depiction grand. Compose for me a rhapsody.\"\n\nThe poet bowed deeply: \"I dare receive the King's gracious command. I humbly withdraw to sharpen my brush and arrange my words.\"\n\nHe composed:\n\nThe moon wanders through Ruibin; the sun dwells in Dongjing.\nThe azure dragon holds the center; the red quail spreads its display.\nNow the orioles sing their harmony, welcoming the long spring days.\nIn this season of nurturing all things, we awaited perfect harvest.\n\nYet month after month drought held sway. We gazed for clouds, but found only shimmer.\nThe primal yang grew fierce and cruel. Burning vapor rose from all quarters.\nFire-chariots were driven; the planet Mars was mounted.\nXihe shook the crimson banner. All blazed and glowed, terrible and bright.\nHeat poured down like torrents; the air shimmered and scorched.\nThe fire-wells boiled; the valleys burned dry. The western deep roasted; even the marshlands turned red.\nRock caves wept no moisture. Reservoirs laid bare their gates.\nDike-ridges became hills; channels turned to cracked earth.\n\nAt such a time, though Zhengbai opened the waters of Jing and Wei, though Baoqi devised his marshlands—what leverage, what conduit could conjure clouds or command rain?\n\nThen they consulted Shen-nong's book on rain-calling. They examined the ancient rites of the rain-dance. Every spirit was invoked—at this altar, at that shrine, through mountains and streams, across hills and hollows. They sought everywhere, performed everywhere. Yet lingering silence met their pleas. The heavens withheld their gift. Complaints rose to the Cloud-River. Accusations flew to the Wind-Lord.\n\nAt last shamans danced and called forth serpents. They fashioned mud-dragons and stone-oxen. Some sealed their gates to halt the drought; others moved the market and dug new channels. Ten thousand mouths cried out together: \"Rain! Oh rain, come forth!\" Yet still nothing came.\n\nThen suddenly the eight winds ceased their flight. The six qi sank into stillness. Sky grew murky; clouds gathered thick. Darkness upon darkness. Silence upon silence.\n\nAbruptly heaven turned and earth rolled. The Supremer Powers revealed their dread majesty. They rebuked the Six Ding-generals. They summoned the Five Stars in haste. They commanded Feilian to meet Fengrong. They scourged the Lightning-Mother; they whipped Lei-gong, the Thunder Lord. Drums of spirits thundered; dragon-carriages rose. Iron cavalry charged; golden cords flew forth. In the western wilds they slew the fire-fiend. In the southern reaches they stormed the arrogant sun.\n\nThen the King issued decree: \"Summon Fengyi, invoke Hairuò!\" Commands were given to the Four Waters. Talismans were sent to the Five Peaks. The stagnant air rose and steamed. Liquid essence permeated and wandered.\n\nThe Rain-Master took his station. Heaven's One held dominion. The signals were raised with perfect order; the proclamations came with measured cadence. Not violent, not wild. Not sluggish, not swift. No tremor, no rupture. No overwhelming, no waste. Gently it moistened and seeped. Richly it washed and caressed. As if some unseen hand gauged and dispensed with perfect restraint.\n\nFirst, light spray descended like dew. Then sheets poured down like balm. The roots that had withered sprouted forth. The shoots that had wilted bloomed again. What had curled emerged; what had bent grew straight. What had paled turned red; what had darkened grew white. All verdure stirred with life. All burgeoned in profusion.\n\nTen thousand things exulted. Every grain swelled its ear. Stems thrust upward; blossoms glistened. Husks split open; heads expanded. Bright and clear they rose—thick upon the field. Purple down adorned them—close-set and dense. One stalk produced ten stems. One stem bore nine ears. Great clusters hung heavy, dark and lustrous. Full and generous they emerged.\n\nStems intertwined with virtue; ears revealed prodigies. The Zhou's bounty seemed meager by comparison. What need to speak of the Han's six-fold harvests?\n\nOh! Earth is mother; Heaven is father. They nurture all things. They give us sweet milk. Yet were heaven to rain gold until hills formed, shoots could not sprout and flourish. Were heaven to rain jade for three days, people could not gather grain to eat.\n\nThus this universal nectar—who bestowed it? Whose gift is this?\n\nBefore the poet finished, a Hanlin scholar rose and sighed deeply. He came forward and spoke:\n\n\"You know only that prayers for rain received response. You do not know the cause of rain itself. You know only heaven in heaven. You do not know how the Sage communes with heaven. Did you not witness how our King responds to heaven's will? He embodies the One Primal Qi; he preserves the One Virtue. He illuminates the Nine Categories; he follows the Nine Constants. He harmonizes yin and yang within their bounds; he orders the Seven Governors by the celestial sphere. Thus he deputizes for heaven's work; he performs heaven's office.\n\nWith reverent care and diligent heart, with watchful eye upon all governance, he honors Shen-nong and reveres Houji. Himself he labors in the sacrificial fields to provide grain for the rituals. He recalls the ancient Bin-wind, examining the harvest directives. Knowing well the ardor of farming, he broods constantly on agricultural affairs.\n\nWhen drought delayed the rains beyond their season, his sacred concern deepened. He trembled at heaven's power. He grieved for the people's suffering. He reduced his meals; he suspended music. He issued urgent edicts lamenting drought. He sought counsel from elder ministers of great renown. He asked wisdom from righteous scholars. He invited their cooperation to correct his shortcomings. He elevated the worthy; he dismissed the base. He remedied what was lacking; he reformed what was corrupt.\n\nHe reduced sentences for grave crimes; he freed those held for lesser offenses. He remitted debts and arrears. He relieved the destitute. He revoked the forced-removal order. He lightened the corvée. His mercy in reviewing cases ran deep; his benevolence in sustaining life was abundant.\n\nThus all hearts rejoiced. The will of heaven could not fail to respond. So heaven answered with sweet rain—its benevolence descended. Truly, \"heaven's hearing comes through the people's ears.\" The Sage's virtue matches heaven itself.\n\nCould mere sacrifices to mountains, mere clay-dragon prayers, produce such world-turning power, such heaven-moving force? But when virtue withers and compassion dies, when realm falls and governance burns—then people suffer drought and heaven sends drought alike. What response could follow?\n\nAh, how our King reveres heaven—with reality, not mere form!\"\n\nThe poet bowed twice, then spoke:\n\n\"How great! The King's virtue matches heaven's! Your words ring true. Yet I have a question. In ancient times, the sage-king Yao revered heaven itself—why then nine years of deluge? The sage-king Tang honored the heavenly way—why then seven years of drought? Even the worthy King Xuan of Zhou, who feared heaven, could not escape the Cloud-River's lament. Our King reveres heaven so faithfully—yet even he faced the drought of yisi. Is his virtue at odds with heaven? Or does the unalterable rhythm of time confound all human effort?\n\nIf the heavenly way lies so distant and obscure, how can human action have purchase?\"\n\nThe scholar gazed upward and proclaimed:\n\n\"You do not understand: when heaven reproves a ruler, it is supreme love for that ruler. When heaven reproved Yao, Shun took it as a warning and tested himself. When heaven reproved Tang, he personally examined himself through six reflections. When heaven reproved King Xuan, he trembled with reverence.\n\nOur King, in receiving heaven's reproof, himself says: 'The fault is mine alone.' I observe him seeking its cause. It was not causeless blame. Perhaps there remained at court those four villains yet unremoved—thus his regret at the difficulty of knowing men. Perhaps he stood amid the upheaval of court and throne—thus his shame at summoning heaven's punishment. Perhaps he cried, 'Let it fall upon me!'—did he not inherit the remnant calamities of the wicked kings before?\n\nOur King withdrew from the throne and sought his error. Is there not perhaps some human shortcoming? Thus heaven's reproof serves to awaken him—it is the hidden kindness of heaven's love. Understanding how the Sage responds to heaven—this is his own spiritual transformation reaching the highest clarity.\n\nBehold the truth: a ruler's greatest path to blessing lies in accepting fault and correcting himself. Thus he received heaven's recompense, seasonably nurturing all creatures. His perfection matches heaven. He stands in direct communion with the Supreme Powers.\n\nWould he boast of being blameless, trusting in fate and neglecting reflection? Behold the glory! Unlike the Han emperor's arrogance in seeking immortality, unlike the Lord of Lu's vain wish to expose the crippled—these but invited heaven's wrath. They blamed years for their ruin and ended not knowing their fault. What remedy could that bring to a wasted realm and suffering people?\"\n\nHereupon the poet changed countenance, moved in his very heart. He rose from his seat and yielded to the scholar, requesting he compose the concluding hymn:\n\n\"Radiant our King,\nVirtue matching the upper sky.\nSingle and sincere—\nSincerity knows no bounds.\nWhere sincerity reaches, heaven responds.\nThe heavenly powers stir.\nTurbid qi retreats; peace descends.\nWarm breath ascends and steams.\nSweet nectar falls—\nHeaven's grace profound and abundant,\nMoist and generous.\nAll things are nurtured.\nRain arrives in season; wind at its time.\nSeason harmonies; year flourishes.\nBehold the utmost of kingship!\nHeaven and human unite.\nUpper and lower answer one another.\nAll together rejoice!\"\n\nThe poet took up his brush with joy and continued:\n\n\"I have heard that in ages of great peace, the five grains do not fail. Night brings unfailing gentle rain. Day brings unfailing soft wind. Wind blows seventy-two times; rain falls thirty-six times. Such is heaven's pattern. The grain grows ever finer. People need not labor. Heaven itself provides encouragement.\n\nIn ancient days, lands yielded twice-ripened rice each year. Counties sent tribute of eight harvests of silk. Is this not such a time? What could surpass it?\"\n\nHe set down his brush and bowed:\n\n\"The rhapsody is complete. I respectfully prepare it for presentation. Let it be circulated among the musical odes.\"\n\nWhen the King had read it through, he humbly declined all credit, saying to the Minister of Agriculture: \"I shall go forth to observe the fields.\"\n\nHe commanded the officials to prepare the official carriage and proceeded to the eastern suburbs, where he summoned the Director of Cultivation. He ascended the ritual field and encouraged the farmers:\n\n\"You who sustain life bear the burden of hunger's fear. Heaven's eye is kind. It has not abandoned me. First came drought; then came rain. The soil grows rich. Plow and sow without delay. Weed and fertilize with your full strength. Through your efforts, abundance comes. Let us together achieve sufficiency.\"\n\nThe village elders all cried \"Ten thousand years!\" and together sang the striker's song:\n\n\"Our early grain and late grain, our ripening grain—\nAcross the fields and lowlands they grow.\nThe father plows; the son plants.\nWe live by their yield.\nWhen drought held sway like burning fire,\nNow that rain has come, like mother's milk,\nThe shoots stand tall and bright.\nThey grow and strengthen day by day.\nOur King communes with heaven—\nHow could harvest fail?\"\n\nThen they sang a reply:\n\n\"From one seed falls ten thousand fruits.\nFrom a single grain splits two.\nIn the threshing-floor, in the granary,\nWe gather, we store.\nWe have grain aplenty, kept in field corners—\nWho would gather it?\nThe realm has grain surplus, stored with the people—\nNot sealed in state vaults.\nThis abundance of harvest—\nWho is the greatest farmer?\nIs it the King? Is it heaven?\nWhat virtue! What grace!\"\n\nAs their song ended, fragrant winds from the south arose. Dark clouds gathered in the west. Soon rain fell again—as if heaven itself bore witness. \n\nQuickly the oppressive heat dissolved. The roads became clear. The King commanded his attendants, and the imperial carriage returned.\n\nDrums beat along the road. Musicians played in procession. Songs answered one another. Crowds gathered like marketplaces. Together they brought forth the wealth of the Eastern Sea and treasures of the Southern Mountains—singing praises of the King's virtue, uttering blessings for his long life. The sound shook all the lands.\n\nAh! The King's virtue extends as far as heaven, as broad as earth. His grace falls like rain, like wind—incomparable, infinite. All beings flourish in his care."
  footnotes:
    - 'Zimozike (子墨客卿): A personification of ink, suggesting poetic inspiration itself. The figure draws from Yang Xiong''s ''Rhapsody on the Feather Hunt.'''
    - 'The nine grains (九農): According to the Rites of Zhou, these are nine varieties of grain including millet, rice, and beans.'
    - 'The four malefactors: In ancient Chinese history, these were Gong-gong, Huan-dou, Gun, and the San-miao—destructive figures who operated during Yao''s reign and were only removed under Shun.'
    - 'The drought of yisi (乙巳): References a historical drought during the era in which this text was written, suggesting the King''s virtue did not prevent all natural calamities—a deliberate theological point about the limits of human agency.'
    - 'Heaven''s hearing comes through the people''s ears (天聽自我民): A classical allusion emphasizing that heavenly will manifests through the people''s welfare and the ruler''s response to their needs.'
    - 'The striker''s song and reply: Traditional folk songs expressing gratitude for harvest and good governance, celebrating the cooperation between ruler, heaven, and laboring people.'
